["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Acton was born about 1504, in Hall End, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Richard Pierce ,Percy in 1531, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1504–":"umbes 1504–Surnud","1500–1553":"1500–1553","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1555–1605":"1555–1605","1504–Female":"1504–Surnud","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","about 1504":"umbes 1504","1531":"1531","1553":"1553","1540":"1540","Abt 1555":"umbes 1555","about 1540":"umbes 1540","1605":"1605","1504":"1504","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pearce Hall, West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Hall End, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United King